THE QUARTILE CODE: A Formal Mathematical Architecture for Civilizational State-Space Analysis

Doctoral Dissertation

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

ABSTRACT (Final)

This dissertation establishes the mathematical foundations for a formal state-space architecture of human civilization. We derive, from first principles, a four-dimensional bounded Euclidean state-space \mathcal{G} = [0,10]^4 \subset \mathbb{R}^4 whose axes correspond to the irreducible dimensions of human social reality: Individual Interior (consciousness), Individual Exterior (behavior), Collective Interior (culture), and Collective Exterior (systems). The derivation proceeds from two universal categorical distinctions (Individual/Collective, Interior/Exterior) whose Cartesian product yields exactly four mutually orthogonal dimensions, proven via group-theoretic decomposition in §3. We define a weighted Mahalanobis metric on \mathcal{G} that respects the heteroscedastic uncertainty of social indicators while maintaining geometric interpretability. The dynamical core of the framework is a non-linear system \dot{\mathbf{G}} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{G} + \mathbf{N}(\mathbf{G}) + \mathbf{E}(t), where \mathbf{A} \in \mathbb{R}^{4\times4} captures linear interactions, \mathbf{N} encodes saturation and phase-transition behavior via logistic damping, and \mathbf{E} represents exogenous forcing. We introduce the Desynchronization Index \Delta = \|P(\mathbf{G})\| where P projects onto the subspace spanned by (G₄-G₃, G₂-G₁), conjectured to correlate with civilizational instability. The interaction matrix \mathbf{A} is shown to be identifiable via Bayesian inference from minimal temporal samples, with closed-form bounds on estimator variance. The framework satisfies formal falsifiability criteria: perfect quadrant correlation would collapse dimensionality; failure of indicator convergence would violate the measurement model; persistent predictive failure would disconfirm the dynamical hypothesis. This work constitutes the first complete mathematical architecture for civilizational analysis—a formal language in which empirical questions can be posed with precision, even when empirical answers await future research.

Keywords: State-Space Analysis, Complex Systems, Mathematical Sociology, Dimensionality Reduction, Desynchronization Theory, Gilium Code

