CHAPTER 6: IDENTIFIABILITY AND INFERENCE

6.1 The Inverse Problem

Given observations \{\mathbf{G}(t_1), \ldots, \mathbf{G}(t_n)\}, can we recover \mathbf{A}, \mathbf{N}, and \mathbf{E}?

6.2 Identifiability of Linear Systems

Theorem 6.1: For a linear system \dot{\mathbf{G}} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{G} with n observations at distinct times, \mathbf{A} is uniquely identifiable if and only if the observation times span at least 4 linearly independent state configurations.

Proof sketch: The matrix \mathbf{A} has 16 parameters. Each observation provides 4 equations (one per quadrant derivative). With n observations, we have 4n equations. For n=4, we have 16 equations—potentially sufficient. The condition for uniqueness is that the matrix of state vectors [\mathbf{G}(t_1), \ldots, \mathbf{G}(t_n)]^T has full rank. ∎

6.3 Bayesian Inference

When observations are insufficient for unique identification, we adopt a Bayesian approach:

Definition 6.1: The posterior distribution over \mathbf{A} given data \mathcal{D} is:

p(\mathbf{A} \mid \mathcal{D}) \propto p(\mathcal{D} \mid \mathbf{A}) p(\mathbf{A})

where:

· p(\mathbf{A}) is a prior encoding theoretical expectations (e.g., sign constraints, sparsity)
· p(\mathcal{D} \mid \mathbf{A}) is the likelihood under a Gaussian error model

Theorem 6.2: Under a Gaussian prior \mathbf{A} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{A}_0, \mathbf{\Sigma}_A) and Gaussian observation noise, the posterior is Gaussian with closed-form mean and covariance.

Proof: Standard result for linear Gaussian systems. ∎

6.4 Identifiability with Non-Linearity

Non-linear terms introduce additional parameters. Identifiability requires either:

· Dense temporal sampling to resolve functional form
· Theoretical constraints reducing the function space (e.g., logistic form with few parameters)

