CHAPTER 7: FORMAL FALSIFIABILITY

7.1 The Scientific Status of the Framework

A mathematical framework is not an empirical hypothesis. But it can be falsifiable in the sense that certain empirical findings would undermine its utility or validity.

7.2 Falsification Conditions

Condition F1 (Dimensional Collapse): If empirical analysis (e.g., PCA on indicator sets) consistently yields fewer than 4 dominant factors explaining >80% variance across diverse societies, the claimed dimensionality is falsified.

Condition F2 (Indicator Non-Convergence): If within-quadrant indicators fail to correlate (Cronbach's α < 0.5) across multiple societies, the quadrant construct lacks empirical coherence.

Condition F3 (Predictive Failure): If the dynamical model (with estimated parameters) systematically fails out-of-sample predictions (error > 2σ across 3+ cases), the dynamical hypothesis is disconfirmed.

Condition F4 (Metric Inconsistency): If the Mahalanobis distance yields counterintuitive rankings (e.g., hunter-gatherers closer to industrial societies than to agricultural societies), the metric requires revision.

7.3 Immunization Strategies (Forbidden)

The following are not permitted as defenses against falsification:

· "Pre/trans fallacy" arguments that reinterpret counter-evidence as confirmation
· Ad hoc adjustments to indicator weights after seeing results
· Appeals to "higher levels" inaccessible to measurement

The framework stands or falls on its ability to generate coherent, testable, and (potentially) falsifiable claims.

