APPENDICES

Appendix A: Group-Theoretic Derivation

Theorem A.1: The four quadrants form a Klein four-group under composition of distinctions.

Proof: Define transformations: T_I (toggle individual/collective), T_M (toggle interior/exterior). Then T_I^2 = T_M^2 = \text{id}, and T_I T_M = T_M T_I. The group generated is isomorphic to \mathbb{Z}_2 \times \mathbb{Z}_2, which has exactly four elements—corresponding to the four quadrants. ∎

Appendix B: Metric Properties

Theorem B.1: The weighted Mahalanobis distance satisfies the metric axioms:

1. d_M(\mathbf{G},\mathbf{H}) \geq 0, equality iff \mathbf{G}=\mathbf{H}
2. d_M(\mathbf{G},\mathbf{H}) = d_M(\mathbf{H},\mathbf{G})
3. Triangle inequality: d_M(\mathbf{G},\mathbf{H}) \leq d_M(\mathbf{G},\mathbf{K}) + d_M(\mathbf{K},\mathbf{H})

Proof: Standard properties of Mahalanobis distance. ∎

Appendix C: Identifiability Proofs

Theorem C.1: For the linear system with logistic damping, the parameter vector \boldsymbol{\theta} = (\text{vec}(\mathbf{A}), \boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\gamma}, \boldsymbol{\delta}, \boldsymbol{\theta}_c) is identifiable if and only if the observation set includes trajectories crossing the saturation regime.

Proof sketch: Logistic damping only affects dynamics near saturation. Without observations in that regime, \boldsymbol{\beta} is unidentifiable. ∎

Appendix D: Desynchronization Bounds

Theorem D.1: For any trajectory satisfying \dot{\mathbf{G}} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{G} with \mathbf{A} stable, \Delta(t) is bounded.

Proof: Express \Delta^2 = \mathbf{G}^T \mathbf{P} \mathbf{G} where \mathbf{P} projects onto the desynchronization subspace. Then \dot{\Delta^2} = \mathbf{G}^T (\mathbf{A}^T\mathbf{P} + \mathbf{P}\mathbf{A}) \mathbf{G}. For stable \mathbf{A}, this quadratic form is negative definite for large \|\mathbf{G}\|, ensuring boundedness. ∎

