DEFENSE PREPARATION: MATHEMATICAL Q&A

Q: Why Euclidean space? Why not a manifold with curvature?
A: Euclidean space is the null model—the simplest structure consistent with the axioms. If empirical distributions reveal curvature (e.g., societies cluster non-linearly), we can later embed \mathcal{G} in a Riemannian manifold. But starting with curvature would over-parameterize without justification.

Q: Your "proof" of orthogonality is logical, not empirical. Does that matter?
A: Logical orthogonality establishes that the axes are conceptually independent. Empirical orthogonality (low correlation across societies) is a separate claim—one we do not make. The framework accommodates any empirical correlation structure; it only requires that the axes be definable independently.

Q: The Desynchronization Index is interesting, but can you prove it correlates with instability?
A: That is an empirical conjecture, not a mathematical theorem. We state it as such. Mathematics provides the language for the conjecture; history provides the test.

Q: Isn't this just dimensional analysis applied to society?
A: Yes—and that is precisely the contribution. Dimensional analysis in physics extracts fundamental units (mass, length, time) from phenomena. We extract fundamental dimensions (G₁–G₄) from human social reality. The analogy is intentional and productive.

Q: Why four? Why not three or five?
A: Because the generating distinctions (individual/collective, interior/exterior) are binary. Their product yields exactly four. Any third distinction would need to be as universal as these two—and none has been demonstrated across cultures and history.

